data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3.3+ supports a **generic `DynamicData`** attribute that uses tuples instead of `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<string, bool>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string, bool)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `DynamicData` → `DynamicData<string, bool>` — generic type params match the test method signature
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — value tuples instead of object arrays
- `["valid@email.com", true]` → `("valid@email.com", true)` — tuple syntax

This gives you compile-time type checking on both the data source and the attribute binding. Mismatched types will fail at build time rather than at runtime. Requires **MSTest.TestFramework ≥ 3.3.0**.
